07866nam a22010575i 9780774863698DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a2020438290  a97807748636987 a10.59962/97807748636982doi  a(DE-B1597)661718  a(OCoLC)1142101549  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA00aHV3021.A35bA37 2020 4aHV3021.A35bA37 2020 7aSOC0570002bisacsh04a362.4084/622304aThe Aging–Disability Nexus /ced. by Katie Aubrecht, Carla Rice, Christine Kelly. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDisability Culture and Politics00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tConceptualizing the Nexus -- tAging and Disability -- tSpectres of Unproductive Life -- tCripping Care Advice -- tDancing In and Out of Control -- tPolitics of Care -- tAging, Disability, and Long-Term-Care Policy -- tDirectly Funded Home Care for Older Adults -- tAge, Disability, and Encounters with Care -- tPower, Agency, Aging, and Cognitive Impairment -- tRegulation of “Care” in Long-Term-Care Homes in Ontario -- tTimescapes and Landscapes -- tAging with and into Disability -- tFrom Boomer to Zoomer -- tDeconstructing Dependency and Development in Global Dementia Policy -- tAging and Disability in the Time of AIDS -- tDisability, Age, the British Countryside, and Social Exclusion -- tSpeaking from the Nexus -- tThinking into Aging–Disability Nexuses -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs the global population ages, disability demographics are shifting. Societal transformation and global health inequities have changed who is likely to reach old age, who is likely to live with disability, and the relationship between aging and disability in various socio-cultural and geopolitical contexts. The Aging–Disability Nexus breaks new ground by bringing gerontology and disability studies into dialogue with each other through a variety of empirical, conceptual, and pedagogical approaches. Contributors explore the tensions that shape the way disability and aging are understood, experienced, and responded to at both individual and systemic levels, while avoiding the common tendency to conflate these overlapping elements and map them onto a normative, faulty notion of the human life trajectory. This perceptive work analyzes the distinction between aging with a disability and aging into disability, and reveals how multiple identities, socio-economic forces, culture, and community give form to our experiences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAging. 0aOlder people with disabilitiesxCare. 0aOlder people with disabilitiesxLong-term care. 0aOlder people with disabilitiesxServices for. 0aOlder people with disabilitiesxSocial conditions. 0aOlder people with disabilities. 0aOlder people. 0aPeople with disabilities. 70(DE-588)10579378270(DE-627)7955498140(DE-576)413939774aDisability Studies2gnd 70(DE-588)12589827730(DE-627)1805726757aAltersdiskriminierung2gnd 70(DE-588)4001446-00(DE-627)1048145780(DE-576)208842918aAlter2gnd 70(DE-588)4005279-50(DE-627)1045409660(DE-576)20886007XaBehinderter Mensch2gnd 70(DE-588)4011404-10(DE-627)1063529380(DE-576)208893350aDemenz2gnd 70(DE-588)4012472-10(DE-627)1063483100(DE-576)20889862XaDiskriminierung2gnd 70(DE-588)4044683-90(DE-627)1048062810(DE-576)209061928aParkinson-Krankheit2gnd 70(DE-588)4071757-40(DE-627)1060970160(DE-576)209184817aGerontologie2gnd 70(DE-588)4112696-80(DE-627)1058353230(DE-576)209470100aBehinderung2gnd 70(DE-588)4449808-10(DE-627)2269872990(DE-576)212